  "signature": "ed25519:b1c2d3e4f5061728394a5b6c7d8e9f0a1b2c3d4e5f6071829303132333435363738393a3b3c3d3e3f40",
  "hasCredibilityFactor": [
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Software quality assurance",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 4,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Version-controlled solver with documented test suite achieving >= Gradation 4 SQA practices; all regression tests passing.",
      "rationale": "The CFD solver (ANSYS Fluent 2022R2) is maintained under ISO 9001-certified quality management. A full regression suite of 412 test cases was executed prior to the study run; all passed. Version control and build traceability records are archived per FDA 21 CFR Part 11 requirements. SQA level assessed as Gradation 4, meeting the MRL 5 requirement."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Method of manufactured solutions (MMS) or equivalent analytical benchmark demonstrating correct order-of-accuracy for all governing equation terms relevant to hemolysis prediction.",
      "rationale": "MMS was applied to the incompressible Navier-Stokes solver kernel; spatial order of accuracy confirmed at 1.92 (expected 2nd order). The scalar hemolysis transport equation was verified against an analytical solution for a Couette flow configuration. One turbulence closure term (rotation correction) lacked a published analytical benchmark; this gap reduces the achieved level to Gradation 3 against the required Gradation 4."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 4,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Grid convergence index (GCI) < 3% on primary QoI (hemolysis index) across all five operating points using at least three systematically refined meshes.",
      "rationale": "Three structured hexahedral meshes (2.1M, 8.4M, 33.6M cells; refinement ratio r=2) were generated. Richardson extrapolation yielded GCI values of 1.8%, 2.1%, 1.6%, 2.0%, and 1.9% at the five operating points. All GCI values are below the 3% threshold. The asymptotic convergence ratio was 0.98–1.02, confirming monotonic convergence. Discretization error meets Gradation 4."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Experimental boundary conditions (inlet flow rate, rotational speed, fluid viscosity, temperature) must match simulation inputs within ±2% at all five operating points; environmental controls documented.",
      "rationale": "Experimental conditions were controlled with calibrated mass flow meters (±0.8%) and tachometers (±0.5 RPM). Fluid temperature was maintained at 37±0.3°C. However, the blood analog viscosity was measured at a single shear rate; shear-thinning characterization was not performed, introducing an unquantified boundary condition uncertainty at low-shear regions near the pump inlet. This limitation reduces the achieved level from 4 to 3."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 4,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Quantitative comparison metric (e.g., E_rel or NRMSE) between predicted and measured hemolysis index <= 15% at all operating points; statistical significance assessed.",
      "rationale": "Normalized relative error between CFD-predicted and experimentally measured hemolysis index ranged from 4.2% to 12.8% across the five operating points (mean 8.3%). A Wilcoxon signed-rank test confirmed no systematic bias (p=0.31). Prediction intervals from the Monte Carlo UQ sweep encompassed all experimental measurements. Output comparison meets Gradation 4."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 5,
      "achievedLevel": 4,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "The QoI used in validation (hemolysis index) must be identical to the clinical decision QoI; no surrogate metrics permitted at MRL 5.",
      "rationale": "The primary QoI is the normalized index of hemolysis (NIH) computed directly from predicted shear stress and exposure time via the Giersiepen-Wurzinger power-law model. The same NIH metric is used in both the validation experiments and the regulatory submission. One secondary QoI (platelet activation state) was not modeled, representing a residual gap. Achieved level is Gradation 4; required level is Gradation 5 for MRL 5."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 4,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation experiments must use the same pump geometry, fluid, and operating envelope as the COU; no geometric simplifications permitted.",
      "rationale": "Validation was performed on the FDA generic centrifugal pump geometry, which is identical to the COU geometry. Operating points span the full clinical flow-speed envelope (3–6 L/min, 2500–3500 RPM). Blood analog fluid (glycerol-water, matched viscosity) was used in lieu of whole blood, which is a recognized limitation but consistent with FDA guidance. Relevance to COU assessed as Gradation 4."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Iterative convergence to residual tolerance <= 1e-6 for all equations; round-off error analysis documented; double-precision arithmetic confirmed.",
      "rationale": "Simulations were run in double precision. Continuity and momentum residuals converged to 1e-7; hemolysis scalar residual converged to 1e-6. Round-off error was not formally analyzed via interval arithmetic; the team relied on double-precision floating point as sufficient mitigation. This gap in formal round-off analysis reduces the achieved level to Gradation 3."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 4,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Simulation setup reviewed by independent analyst; checklist-based verification of boundary conditions, material properties, and solver settings; all discrepancies resolved prior to results extraction.",
      "rationale": "An independent CFD analyst (not involved in model setup) performed a structured peer review using a 47-item checklist covering boundary condition assignment, turbulence model selection, material property inputs, and post-processing scripts. Three minor discrepancies were identified and corrected prior to final runs. Use error controls assessed at Gradation 4."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "The constitutive model for hemolysis (power-law damage accumulation) and the turbulence closure (SST k-omega) must be justified against published literature for rotating blood-contacting devices; sensitivity of hemolysis predictions to model form alternatives must be documented.",
      "rationale": "The Giersiepen-Wurzinger power-law hemolysis model was selected based on its widespread use in FDA-recognized pump validation studies and its demonstrated performance in the FDA Critical Path hemolysis benchmark. The SST k-omega turbulence closure was chosen over the realizable k-epsilon model following a qualitative literature review of rotating machinery flows in the hemolysis prediction context. Published comparisons (Fraser et al. 2011, Hariharan et al. 2018) indicate SST k-omega captures the near-wall shear stress distribution more accurately for this class of pump geometry. A qualitative sensitivity assessment was conducted by reviewing model form uncertainty contributions documented in three independent CFD hemolysis studies using the same FDA generic pump; the consensus finding was that power-law model coefficients (alpha, beta) contribute the dominant model form uncertainty, estimated at approximately 18–25% of the total hemolysis index prediction uncertainty. This qualitative assessment, grounded in the published literature and corroborated by the Monte Carlo UQ results in this study, provides sufficient confidence that the model form is appropriate for the COU. No structured level scoring was applied to this factor because the team determined that the qualitative evidence base was more informative than a single integer gradation for communicating model form uncertainty to the regulatory reviewer."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "All model input parameters characterized with probability distributions; Monte Carlo propagation performed; sensitivity indices (Sobol) computed for top-5 inputs.",
      "rationale": "Monte Carlo UQ was performed with 2000 samples. Fluid viscosity, inlet velocity profile, and rotational speed were characterized with normal distributions from calibration data. Power-law hemolysis coefficients (alpha, beta) were assigned literature-derived distributions (log-normal, CV=15%). Sobol first-order indices were computed for five inputs. Gap: pump surface roughness was treated as deterministic (no distribution assigned) due to lack of metrology data on the test article. This reduces the achieved level to Gradation 3."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Minimum n=5 independent experimental replicates per operating point; inter-sample variability characterized; outlier analysis documented.",
      "rationale": "Four independent experimental replicates were performed per operating point (n=4, below the required n=5). Inter-sample coefficient of variation ranged from 6.2% to 11.4% across operating points. One outlier (operating point 3, replicate 2) was identified via Grubbs test (p<0.05) and excluded; the exclusion is documented. The sample size shortfall reduces the achieved level to Gradation 3."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 4,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Simulation input parameters (geometry, boundary conditions, fluid properties) must be shown equivalent to experimental inputs via quantitative comparison; any deviations must be bounded and their impact on QoI assessed.",
      "rationale": "Pump geometry was digitized from the FDA reference CAD file; dimensional verification confirmed maximum deviation of 0.03 mm from nominal. Fluid viscosity equivalency was confirmed within 1.2% at the operating temperature. Inlet velocity profiles were matched using time-averaged PIV measurements as boundary conditions. All parameter equivalencies are within the 2% tolerance band. Equivalency of input parameters meets Gradation 4."
    }
  ],
